In [the selected block](file:///<redacted>/lex/src/liblex.zig#L363-L369), the main issue is not just verbosity.

- [Line 363](file:///<redacted>/lex/src/liblex.zig#L363) sets `self.buffer_modification_index = null;`, so the `if` on [line 365](file:///<redacted>/lex/src/liblex.zig#L365) can never run. If that field is really what you meant, lines 365-369 are redundant and can be removed entirely.
- The comment on [line 364](file:///<redacted>/lex/src/liblex.zig#L364) says `literal_index`, but the code checks `buffer_modification_index`. Based on the comment and the earlier invariant in [lines 227-233](file:///<redacted>/lex/src/liblex.zig#L227-L233), this looks like it should probably be about `literal_index`.
- [Line 367](file:///<redacted>/lex/src/liblex.zig#L367) uses `== null`, which is a comparison, not an assignment. If the intent is to clear the field, it should be `= null`.

If your intent is “after backspace, clear `literal_index` once it falls out of range”, the shortest reasonable rewrite is:

```zig
if (self.literal_index != null and self.literal_index.? == self.buffer_length) {
    self.literal_index = null;
}
```

Why this can stay short:
- Before backspace, you already assert `literal_index < buffer_length`.
- After `self.buffer_length -= 1`, the only invalid case is equality with the new `buffer_length`.
- So you do not need a broader range check.

If you want the more idiomatic Zig form instead of the shortest form, use optional capture:

```zig
if (self.literal_index) |literal_index| {
    if (literal_index == self.buffer_length) {
        self.literal_index = null;
    }
}
```

So the real simplification is:
1. Fix the field mismatch (`literal_index` vs `buffer_modification_index`).
2. Fix the `==`/`=` typo.
3. Collapse the logic to a single equality check, because your invariant already makes anything more complex unnecessary.
